Incident.Summary: Driving a motor vehicle while under the influence of alcohol, and possession of controlled dangerous substance.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
MARYLAND STATE POLICE- FORESTVILLE BARRACK 
THE STOP WAS CAPTURED BY A MOBILE IN-CAR VIDEO RECORDER / BODY CAMERA
Defendant: Johnson, Stephon Derrick Newby
Date of Birth: 12/18/1996
Date of Arrest: 01/21/2023    
Time of Arrest: 0429 Hours
Soundex: J525777139959
 

Narrative
THIS STOP WAS AUDIBLY AND VISUALLY RECORDED. L-22. DUI #-23-MSP-002553
TROOPER M. GIBBONS-ID #7441 MARYLAND STATE POLICE - FORESTVILLE BARRACK &;
CERTIFICATES AND TRAINING:
-NHTSA CERTIFIED TO CONDUCT STANDARDIZED FIELD SOBRIETY TESTS (SFST)
-CERTIFIED PRELIMINARY BREATH TEST (PBT) OPERATOR

SCENE PROCESSING-

All CDS was packaged and processed in accordance with all Maryland State Police policies and procedures.
MSP Form 67/ PH completed and attached. PH # P-339108
Citation # 6Z46637401


DESCRIPTION OF VIOLATION / INCIDENT / TRAFFIC STOP (VEHICLE IN MOTION)-
        On January 21, 2023, at approximately 0043 hours, I, Trooper Gibbons #7441, was patrolling the area of
Southbound I-495, when I observed a gray Toyota Avalon traveling at a high rate of speed.

INITIAL CONTACT WITH DEFENDANT (PERSONAL CONTACT)-
         I observed a gray Toyota Avalon bearing Maryland registration1EM7449; traveling Southbound I-495 at a high rate of speed. I made my way behind the vehicle in my marked patrol vehicle. While traveling behind it, I observed its speed traveling at approximately 114 mph. At that time I activated my emergency equipment and conducted a traffic stop, Southbound I-495 at St. Barnabas Road. I made contact with the driver of the gray Toyota Avalon who was identified through Meters and from is Maryland state ID as Stephon Derrick Newby Johnson, (DOB:12/18/1996, African American male). While speaking with Johnson, I immediately detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from his breath and person. I identified myself to Johnson and informed him that he was being audibly and visibly recorded, and I advised him that I observed him traveling at 114mph in a 55mph zone. Johnson admitted to speeding and confessed that he did not have a Maryland driver's license. Johnson was continuing to talk fast and was also on his cell phone telling whom ever it was that he was going to jail. Johnson stated this twice. I requested an addition unit to respond to my location. At that time Trooper Damiano #7387 arrived to assist. While the driver was still in the vehicle, I smelled the odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from the interior of the vehicle. I asked Johnson to step out of the vehicle in which he complied. I was able to smell a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage on Johnson's breath and person as he continued speaking with me. Johnson's speech was slurred, and his eyes were glassy. I asked Johnson if he had consumed an alcoholic beverage prior to driving, and he stated that he had 1 alcoholic beverage. Johnson stated that he had consumed two shots of patron two hours before driving. While speaking with Johnson, I observed his eyes to be glassy. I informed Johnson that I would be performing standardized field sobriety tests (SFST) on him to which he agreed. At this time, Johnson reached into his left jacket pocket and handed me a plastic bag containing a greenish brown vegetable matter of suspected CDS, cannabis less than 10 grams. Based on my training, knowledge, and experience, I am able to identify the suspected CDS as cannabis. Johnson advised that this was all that he had.


PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)
The evaluation was performed on the right shoulder of Southbound I-495 at St. Barnabas Road.
The surface was dry, level, and free from any obvious debris after clearing. The weather was clear.
Lighting was dark. My patrol vehicles forward emergency lights were deactivated during all three tests.
Johnson appeared to be in good physical condition and did not display any visible injuries.
Johnson was asked the following questions:
Glasses or Contacts - None
Medical Conditions - None
Injuries - None
Medication - None


HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (6/6 clues observed)
The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. The tip of a pen was used as the test
Stimulus and held approximately 12 inches Johnson's; eyes. Johnson was instructed to look forward keeping his head still while following and focusing on the tip of the stimulus with his eyes until told to stop. Johnson's pupils were equal in size and showed equal tracking. Johnson was positioned in a manner to ensure the headlights of passing traffic would not interfere with the test results. While administering this test, Johnson moved his head on several occasions. Johnson had to be reminded not to move his head.
1.) Lack of Smooth Pursuit - Present in both eyes
2.) Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation - Present in both eyes
3.) Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees - Present in both eyes
WALK AND TURN - (6/8 clues observed).
Prior to Johnson performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be performed. I asked Johnson if he understood the test, and he advised he understood.
Instructional stage:
1). Lost balance-Feet broke apart, and he stepped offline during the beginning.
Walking Stage (1st Nine):
1). Missed heal to toe on all steps.
2). Stepped offline 2x
3). Raised his arms more than six inches from his body.
4). Improper Turn.
5). Stopped during the first 9 steps.
Turn: Incomplete
Walking Stage (2nd Nine):
1.) Missed heal to toe on all steps.
2.) Stepped offline 2x
3.) Raised his arms more than six inches from his body.
Completed test improperly.


ONE LEG STAND (0/4 clues observed)
Prior to Johnson performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be.
Johnson was asked if he understood the test and the instructions. Johnson advised he did.


Balance and Count Stage:
N/A

ARREST:
Based on the following, I had probable cause to believe Johnson was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol:
* Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from the interior of the vehicle.
* Glassy eyes.
* Slurred speech.
* My observed signs of impairment as Johnson performed field sobriety tests.
* Failed to maintain balance.
* The defendant was traveling southbound I-495 at a high rate of speed of 114 Mph.
* Admitted to consuming an alcoholic beverage prior to driving
  •  Admitted to having what appeared to be CDS (cannabis) on his person.
  • I was able to smell a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage on Johnson's breath and person as he continued speaking with me.
Johnson was placed under arrest for Driving While Under the Influence of Alcohol.
Johnson was placed in the front passenger seat per department policy and transported to the
Maryland State Police Forestville Barrack:

(Brandon Mitchell Johnson, DOB: 02/09/1995, 1M), the owner of the Toyota Avalon arrived at the scene to take possession of the vehicle.

       Johnson was read the DR-15 Advice of Rights form in English via audio at which time Johnson refused to take the breath test at 0516 hours. Johnson was given all copies of pertinent paperwork, and was released on citations to a valid driver. The above listed evidence was then packaged and processed per Maryland State Police policy and procedure, forwarded to Maryland State Police Crime Lab to be tested.
 
All events occurred in Prince George's County, Maryland.

IncidentProperty.Description: 1 zip lock bag containing 3.85 grams of suspected marijuana.
